Is this intended or an oversight?

## Issue description

As it stands now, compiling with clang 3.4 (assuming the same goes for clang 3.3) makes clang segfault. To work around this, Valloric/ycmd#925 had to drop support for clang 3.3 and clang 3.4.

Looking at [the current `ycm_core.cpp`](https://github.com/bstaletic/ycmd/blob/pybind11_rfc/cpp/ycm/ycm_core.cpp) and [the last year's segfaults](https://travis-ci.org/bstaletic/ycmd/jobs/268804565) ([today's segfaults](https://travis-ci.org/bstaletic/ycmd/jobs/362463412) don't look much different to me), @jagerman thought it had something to do with the static variable used in exception binding and told me to try the following in `pybind11.h`. 

```c++
NAMESPACE_BEGIN(detail)
template <typename CppException>
exception<CppException> &get_exception_object() {
    static exception<CppException> ex;
    return ex;
}
NAMESPACE_END(detail)

/**
 * Registers a Python exception in `m` of the given `name` and installs an exception translator to
 * translate the C++ exception to the created Python exception using the exceptions what() method.
 * This is intended for simple exception translations; for more complex translation, register the
 * exception object and translator directly.
 */
template <typename CppException>
exception<CppException> &register_exception(handle scope,
                                            const char *name,
                                            PyObject *base = PyExc_Exception) {
    auto &ex = detail::get_exception_object<CppException>();
    ex = exception<CppException>(scope, name, base);
    register_exception_translator([](std::exception_ptr p) {
        if (!p) return;
        try {
            std::rethrow_exception(p);
        } catch (const CppException &e) {
            detail::get_exception_object<CppException>()(e.what());
        }
    });
    return ex;
}
```

This did solve the segmentation fault (at least on clang 3.4), but is now causing [compilation errors](https://travis-ci.org/bstaletic/ycmd/jobs/362466751).

## Reproducible example code

Unfortunately, I can't make this minimal. Something, somewhere in ycmd libclang completer bindings is making clang 3.3 segfault, but I am willing to run tests on travis.

Since travis only supports clang 3.4, I'll try to package clang 3.3 for my distro so that we can test it. I still can't promise I'll manage to get clang 3.3 ready for testing. I will be using https://github.com/bstaletic/ycmd/tree/pybind11_segfault to test whatever we come up with.

Hello, all!

I have a problem exposing a class with custom operator `new` (custom allocation in a heap book).
Here is an example:

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

class Example {
public:
    static void*    operator new(std::size_t size);
    static void     operator delete(void* p, std::size_t size);
    Example() {}
};

PYBIND11_MODULE(test, m) {
    m.doc() = "test";
    py::class_<Example>(m, "Example")
            .def(py::init<>())
    ;
}
```
The problem arises due to the fact that this statement
```c++
 .def(py::init<>())
```
is a shorthand for
```c++
.def("__init__", [](Example &instance) {new (&instance) Example();}
```
which results in the next error:
`
pybind11/pybind11.h:1320:60: error: no matching function for call to ‘Example::operator new(sizetype, Base*&)’
cl.def("__init__", [](Base *self_, Args... args) { new (self_) Base(args...); }, extra...);
`

It worked in Boost.Python out-of-the-box, because they have, apparently, different way of creating a constructor's bindings.

How it is possible to resolve this problem?

I have following snippet of code, which successfully compiles, but causes `arg(): could not convert default keyword argument into a Python object (type not registered yet?)`.
```
.def("build", [](Unitset& instance, UnitType type, Pybrood::UniversalPosition target) -> bool {
   return instance.build(type, TilePosition(target[0], target[1]));
}, py::arg("type"), py::arg("target") = py::cast(Pybrood::TilePositions::None))
```
No matter what I try here: `Pybrood::TilePositions::None`, `py::cast(Pybrood::TilePositions::None)`, `std::array<int, 2>(Pybrood::TilePositions::None)`, result is the same: compiles then fails in runtime.

`Pybrood::TilePositions::None` is `std::array<int, 2>` constant derived from another constant, not defined by me. That's why I want to preserve it as is.
```
typedef std::array<int, 2> UniversalPosition;
const UniversalPosition None = convert_position<BWAPI::TilePosition>(BWAPI::TilePositions::None);
```
I'm trying to replace custom position classes with simple std::array to get/pass python tuples "out of the box". I suspect this problem hides in some typeid magic, which doesn't allow typedef'ed things to be considered 'registered' without manual registering from scratch.

Please excuse my very shallow knowledge of C++ :fearful: How better could I deal with this problem?

Pybind11 seems to perform conversion between floating point and integer types.

    #include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
    #include <iostream>

    void MyFunction(int i) { std::cout << " integer: " << i << "\n"; }
    void MyFunction(double d) { std::cout << " double: " << d << "\n"; }

    PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
        pybind11::module m("example", "pybind example plugin");
        m.def("MyFunction", static_cast<void(*)(int)>(MyFunction));
        m.def("MyFunction", static_cast<void(*)(double)>(MyFunction));
        return m.ptr();
    }


For example, the integer version of MyFunction will truncate a python float, and the double version will expand a python int. When overloaded, the version of MyFunction called is always whichever was exported first.

This comes from cpython helpfully doing the conversion (ie, in `PyLong_AsLong`) rather than checking the type.

I would think floating point -> integer would be disallowed, since it would almost always truncate. The other direction is possibly ok, although there is risk of loss of precision with large integers (and overloads wouldn't work). The checks are pretty easy to insert, but I was curious of your thoughts of what should be allowed and what shouldn't.

